          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818882?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> &#39;Bel-Air&#39; is among the shows on Peacock.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Erica Parise/PEACOCK/Getty Images </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001062077"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/joe-flint" itemprop="url" rel="author">Joe Flint</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 17, 2023 8:00 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/peacock-becomes-latest-streaming-service-to-raise-prices-1a890bc3"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> NBCUniversal is raising the price of its Peacock streaming service by as much as $2 a month, the latest sign that entertainment companies are putting a greater emphasis on profitability after years of costly investments.</p><p> The price increase comes as Peacock continues to lose money and has been spending more on live sports and original content.</p><p> The service, which has about 22 million subscribers, had a $704 million loss before interest, taxes, depreciation and amortization in the first quarter.</p><p> NBCUniversal parent <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/CMCSA" class="company-name">Comcast</a> has said it expects <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/comcast-cmcsa-q1-earnings-report-2023-1cf2e5ab?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Peacock&#39;s losses to peak</a> around $3 billion in 2023, then steadily improve thereafter. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=58B87759-7D3C-483A-8F80-786E41CB390C&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fpeacock-becomes-latest-streaming-service-to-raise-prices-1a890bc3&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> Subscription price creep is real, and new data show that more consumers are rejecting higher prices on some of their favored subscription streaming and delivery services. WSJ personal tech columnist Nicole Nguyen joins guest host Dion Rabouin.<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>The price for Peacock&#39;s premium plan will increase $1 a month to $5.99 while the advertising-free service tier will increase by $2 per month to $11.99. The change will go into effect immediately for new customers and on Aug. 17 for existing subscribers.</p><p> In a statement, NBCUniversal said the price increase will allow it to continue to invest in strong programming and remain competitive in the marketplace. It is the first price increase since Peacock launched in 2020.</p><p> Peacock has bet heavily on expensive sports to differentiate itself from other streaming platforms. Besides simulcasting NBC&#39;s “Sunday Night Football” franchise, Peacock also streams Premier League soccer and carries Notre Dame and Big Ten football. It is spending about $110 million to have <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/peacock-to-carry-one-nfl-playoff-game-exclusively-next-season-fb339027?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">exclusive rights to an NFL playoff game</a> in the 2023-24 season, The Wall Street Journal previously reported.</p><p> Peacock has also spent more on original shows and has found some success with detective series “Poker Face,” which received four Emmy nominations earlier this month, including a best actress nod for star <a href="https://www.emmys.com/bios/natasha-lyonne" target="_blank" class="icon none">Natasha Lyonne</a> .</p><p> Over the past two years, most major streaming services have raised prices in the US In January of this year, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/WBD" class="">Warner Bros. Discovery</a> <span class="company-name-type">&#39;s</span></p> Max platform monthly fee jumped $1 to $15.99.<p></p><p> Last year, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/NFLX" class="company-name">Netflix</a> upped the prices for all of its plans. The basic package increased $1 to $9.99 a month and the standard plan went up by $1.50 to $15.49 a month.</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/DIS" class="company-name">Walt Disney</a> also raised prices on its Disney+ and Hulu platforms last year. Disney+ with ads costs $7.99 a month while an ad-free version increased $3 to $10.99 a month. Hulu&#39;s ad-free service raised its price by $2 to $14.99 a month and the version with ads went up $1 to $7.99 a month.</p><p> Write to Joe Flint at <a href="mailto:Joe.Flint@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Joe.Flint@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 18 Jul 2023 00:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/peacock-becomes-latest-streaming-service-to-raise-prices-1a890bc3</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/peacock-becomes-latest-streaming-service-to-raise-prices-1a890bc3<author><![CDATA[Joe Flint]]></author><category> Broadcasting</category><category> Television Broadcasting</category><category> Media/Entertainment</category><category> Prices</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>市场/营销</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Comcast Cl A</category><category> CMCSA</category><category> Comcast</category><category> prices</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>市场</category><category>营销</category><category>broadcasting</category><category> television broadcasting</category><category>媒体</category><category>entertainment </category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Restricting Chip Sales to China Could Backfire on U.S., Industry Group Says]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> The potential limits threaten to curtail American semiconductor companies&#39; push for domestic expansion, the SIA warns <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001060362"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=E8DCC2B0-F066-41EA-9053-96EC3A35B05E&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Frestricting-chip-sales-to-china-could-backfire-on-u-s-industry-group-says-dbb7b8df&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> Chip maker Nvidia broke into the exclusive club of companies that have a $1 trillion market cap. WSJ&#39;s Asa Fitch breaks down how Nvidia got there—and why AI is fueling the company&#39;s rapid growth. Photo illustration: Annie Zhao<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001060362"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/asa-fitch" itemprop="url" rel="author">Asa Fitch</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Updated July 17, 2023 6:32 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/restricting-chip-sales-to-china-could-backfire-on-u-s-industry-group-says-dbb7b8df"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> The Biden administration&#39;s potential curbs on sales of advanced semiconductors to China could undermine huge new government investments in domestic chip-making, the US chip-industry trade group said Monday.</p><p> The Biden administration is considering a raft of <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-considers-new-curbs-on-ai-chip-exports-to-china-56b17feb?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">new curbs on the sale of chips</a> to China, aiming to disrupt Beijing&#39;s use of artificial intelligence for hacking and weapons development. At the same time, the administration is rolling out $39 billion in grants for new US chip-making plants after the passage of the <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chips-act-is-bounty-for-semiconductor-companieswith-many-strings-attached-6e72fd67?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Chips Act</a> last year.</p><p> “Allowing the industry to have continued access to the China market, the world&#39;s largest commercial market for commodity semiconductors, is important to avoid undermining the positive impact of this effort,” the Semiconductor Industry Association, the Washington, DC industry body, said in a written statement. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818385?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> President Biden toured a computer-chip factory in Michigan last year.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Patrick Semansky/Associated Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> US chip companies have long argued that the government should carefully weigh the impact of export restrictions, because sales in China support investments in the US and help fund research that sustains their technological edge.</p><p> Chip companies, including the AI-chip leader <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/NVDA" class="">Nvidia</a> <span class="company-name-type">,</span> have been lobbying the administration to refrain from stricter export controls after a ratcheting-up of tensions between the US and China that has centered on the semiconductor and electric-vehicle industries. <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/nvidia-warns-of-lost-opportunities-if-u-s-bans-ai-chip-exports-to-china-293fa911?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Nvidia&#39;s chief financial officer warned</a> of a “permanent loss of opportunities for the US industry” in China if sales of AI chips were prohibited.</p><p> Restrictions the SIA described as overly broad, ambiguous and at times unilateral “risk diminishing the US semiconductor industry&#39;s competitiveness, disrupting supply chains, causing significant market uncertainty, and prompting continued escalatory retaliation by China,” the SIA said. It called on the Biden administration to consult with industry before imposing more restrictions.</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p> The US last October <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-restricts-semiconductor-exports-in-bid-to-slow-chinas-military-advance-11665155702?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">imposed some of the most stringent curbs</a> yet on chips and chip-making equipment, requiring chip companies to seek licenses from the Commerce Department to sell some of their most advanced products to Chinese customers.</p><p> The measures are aimed at preventing US technology from advancing China&#39;s military power.</p><p> “Our actions have been carefully tailored to focus on technology with national security implications, and designed to ensure that US and allied technologies are not used to undermine our national security,” a spokesman for the White House National Security Council said.</p><p> The spokesman added that since passage of the Chips Act last year, “private companies have announced nearly $140 billion in investments in the United States in semiconductor production, supply chains and R&amp;D over the next decade.”</p><p> In the wake of the US actions, China <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/beijing-bans-micron-as-supplier-to-big-chinese-firms-citing-national-security-5f326b90?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">has banned major Chinese companies</a> from buying from US computer-memory company <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/MU" class="">Micron</a> <span class="company-name-type">,</span> and recently imposed restrictions on exports of <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-restricts-exports-of-two-metals-used-in-high-performance-chips-a649402b?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">metals used in cellphone communication chips</a> .</p><p> The Biden administration <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-considers-new-curbs-on-ai-chip-exports-to-china-56b17feb?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">is now considering further restrictions</a> that would snare AI chips that Nvidia developed for the Chinese market. It is also considering cutting off Chinese access to AI chips through <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-looks-to-restrict-chinas-access-to-cloud-computing-to-protect-advanced-technology-f771613?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">cloud-computing companies</a> . President Biden <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-grapples-with-potential-threats-from-chinese-ai-7d1f2e70?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">is expected to restrict US investment</a> in advanced Chinese chip-making, among other technologies, in a coming executive order.</p><p> The industry push comes as the Biden administration tries to find new diplomatic openings with Beijing. Treasury Secretary</p> Janet Yellen traveled to <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/yellen-trip-aids-fragile-effort-by-u-s-china-to-keep-talking-9b78ea55?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Beijing this month</a> amid a flurry of visits by US officials, with limited signs of progress.<p></p><p> Numerous chip companies are planning large chip-making projects in the US after the passage of the Chips Act last year. Among them are <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/INTC" class="">Intel</a> <span class="company-name-type">,</span> Micron, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/SSNHZ" class="company-name">Samsung</a> and <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/TSM" class="">Taiwan Semiconductor Manufacturing</a> <span class="company-name-type">Co.</span> , which together are plowing tens of billions of dollars into new plants that policy makers hope will help reverse the industry&#39;s shift toward Asia in recent decades.</p><p> Write to Asa Fitch at <a href="mailto:asa.fitch@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">asa.fitch@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 17 Jul 2023 22:32:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/restricting-chip-sales-to-china-could-backfire-on-us-industry-group-says-dbb7b8df</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/restricting-chip-sales-to-china-could-backfire-on-us-industry-group-says-dbb7b8df<author><![CDATA[Asa Fitch]]></author><category> Artificial Intelligence Technologies</category><category> Semiconductors</category><category> Wooden Furniture</category><category> Consumer Goods</category><category> Furniture</category><category> Industrial Electronics</category><category>工业品</category><category>Integrated Circuits</category><category> Technology</category><category>法规/政府政策</category><category>Financial Performance</category><category> Earnings</category><category> Sales Figures</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Micron Technology</category><category> MU</category><category> Intel</category><category> INTC</category><category> NVIDIA</category><category> NVDA</category><category> Samsung Electronics</category><category> 005930.SE</category><category> KR:005930</category><category> Taiwan Semiconductor Manufacturing</category><category> 2330.TW</category><category> TW:2330</category><category>规定</category><category>政府政策</category><category>financial performance</category><category> earnings</category><category> sales figures</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>artificial intelligence technologies</category><category> semiconductors</category><category> wooden furniture</category><category> consumer goods</category><category> furniture</category><category> industrial electronics</category><category>工业品</category><category>integrated circuits</category><category> technology </category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Ford Cuts Price of F-150 Lightning Electric Truck by Up to $10,000]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Move comes after rival Tesla begins production of Cybertruck <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001059809"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="504" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818253?width=700&amp;height=504" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Ford is reducing prices as it scales up production and lowers costs.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Ryan Garza/USA TODAY NETWORK/Reuters </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001059809"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/nora-eckert" itemprop="url" rel="author">Nora Eckert</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Updated July 17, 2023 5:02 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ford-cuts-price-of-ev-f-150-lightning-truck-by-up-to-17-2cc21c6a"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/F" class="company-name">Ford</a> slashed prices on its electric F-150 Lightning pickup truck by up to nearly 17% Monday, the latest sign that swelling inventories and fierce price competition are softening the market for the technology the auto industry is betting its future on.</p><p> Ford Motor said Monday that the reductions, which effectively dropped the Lightning&#39;s starting price by almost $10,000 to $49,995, were the result of lower material costs and the company having more factory output. Some versions will get a steeper price cut than others.</p><p> The Lightning is one of Ford&#39;s highest-profile EV launches yet and is key to its growth plans as it aims to transition more of its lineup away from the gasoline-powered vehicles that continue to drive the bulk of its profits.</p><p> Automakers globally have been investing hundreds of billions of dollars to create new electric models, build battery factories and construct new EV plants. The capital binge—in part prompted by tightening carbon-emissions requirements—has over the years generated enthusiasm among investors seeking a growth opportunity in the wake of <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/TSLA" class="">Tesla</a> <span class="company-name-type">&#39;s</span> meteoric <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-problem-with-teslas-ai-rally-in-eight-charts-e72dbb8f?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">rise in stock value</a> .</p><p> Along the way, auto executives have touted strong consumer interest in their latest EV entries, as the companies set ambitious targets for converting their lineups to electrics. Now, Ford&#39;s Lightning price cut is the latest development raising questions about the strength of the budding EV market.</p><p> The pace of sales overall on EVs—while much stronger than the broader car market— <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ev-sales-growth-in-first-half-slows-from-torrid-pace-2bd2790e?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">slowed in the first half</a> of this year. Meanwhile, some car companies are already reporting excess inventory, a reversal of a year earlier when many newly released models had multimonth wait lists.</p><p> Some automakers also have been cutting prices on top-selling EV models.</p><p> Tesla—which had 60% US market share in electric vehicles this year through June, according to Motor Intelligence—reported a <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/tesla-deliveries-to-show-whether-price-cuts-are-paying-off-2f2aac93?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">surge in second-quarter deliveries</a> that was helped by <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/tesla-cuts-prices-again-as-it-seeks-to-lure-new-buyers-bc8394e5?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">sharp price cuts</a> and discounts rolled out earlier this year. Also over the weekend, Tesla <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/tesla-begins-cybertruck-production-after-yearslong-wait-dbff33f?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">began production</a> of its Cybertruck nearly four years after the prototype was introduced.</p><p> Ford in January <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ford-cuts-prices-of-ev-mustang-mach-e-11675090387?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">responded to Tesla&#39;s price cuts</a> by lowering the price on its Mustang Mach-E electric SUV, a direct rival to Tesla&#39;s top-selling Model Y. The Dearborn, Mich., car company reduced prices yet again on the Mach-E in May.</p><p> When first introduced, the Lightning had a starting price tag of around $40,000. However, Ford several times <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ford-raises-price-again-on-electric-f-150-lightning-truck-fe0010ea?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">hiked the sticker price</a> during a period of strong demand and to help offset higher expenses related to materials and the battery inputs.</p><p> Shares of Ford fell 5.9% Monday, following news of the EV pickup&#39;s price cuts.</p><p> Ford Chief Executive Jim Farley</p> has expressed reticence about price cuts on EVs, citing concern that it hurts resale values and brand image. Ford has been able to raise Lightning prices over the past year in part because there are few EV truck options on the market.<p></p><p> “There&#39;s a limit on how far we&#39;ll go,” Farley said of the company&#39;s price cut strategy at a Wall Street Journal event in May. “I think it&#39;s a worrying trend.”</p><p> EV pricing has softened throughout the year as some automakers have followed Tesla&#39;s lead. Industrywide, the average price buyers paid for an EV decreased nearly 20% from June 2022 to last month, according to research firm Cox Automotive. For gas-engine vehicles, prices have remained steady over the same period, increasing slightly to $48,808.</p><p> Electric cars have begun to back up at US dealerships. There were 92 days of unsold EV inventory at the end of June, a measure of stock availability based on recent sales trends, compared with a 51-day supply across all types of vehicles, according to Cox.</p><p> The inventory numbers don&#39;t include Tesla, which sells directly to consumers. In the first quarter, the value of Tesla&#39;s finished goods—a measure that reflects unsold vehicle inventory and those in transit to customers, among other products available for sale—increased to roughly $4.6 billion, up from less than $1 billion the year before, securities filings show.</p><p> Boosting sales of the EV truck has become even more important as Ford aims to significantly increase production. Ford has twice increased its factory output target for the Lightning in the past couple of years and now aims to build about 150,000 electric trucks a year at its plant in suburban Detroit.</p><p> Tesla, too, is aiming to beef up the rate at which it churns out EVs, recently applying for approval to double the size of its factory near Berlin in order to produce up to one million EV cars a year. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=DA8844A5-F592-400E-8432-35B615313E7B&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fford-cuts-price-of-ev-f-150-lightning-truck-by-up-to-17-2cc21c6a&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> Weeks after Tesla slashed prices on a number of its models, Ford Motor dropped the price of its electric Mustang Mach-E. WSJ auto reporter Nora Eckert compares the automakers&#39; strategic moves and explains what this means for the industry. Photo illustration: Josephine Chu<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>The auto industry is under pressure to sell more EVs in part because of stiffening government regulations, not only in the US but also in Europe and China. The Biden administration in April <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/epa-seeks-to-boost-evs-with-toughest-ever-rules-on-tailpipe-emissions-5658217d?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">proposed some of the nation&#39;s toughest-ever restrictions</a> on car pollution, laying out new rules that analysts say would require about two-thirds of all new vehicles sold be EVs by 2032.</p><p> Ford is already losing money on the EVs it sells. It projects that this part of the business <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ford-projects-3-billion-loss-on-ev-business-for-2023-98037e4e?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">could lose $3 billion</a> this year, a figure that it expects to be offset by the profits earned on its gas-engine business.</p><p> Tesla, which continues to dominate the electric-vehicle market globally, has been aggressive in its efforts to grow sales, even if it has come at the expense of <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/tesla-tsla-q1-earnings-report-2023-6b441d30?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">near-term profitability</a> .</p><p> Throughout the year, it has released a series of price adjustments that have effectively taken down the cost of its vehicles between 14% and 28%, depending on the model. Tesla <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/teslas-price-cuts-are-roiling-the-car-market-11674327793?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">has more wiggle room</a> to lower prices because its operating margins are higher than those of its rivals, including Ford.</p><p> Industrywide sales of electric vehicles in the US surged by 50% in the first half of the year, cooling from a 71% rise in the year-earlier period.</p><p> Ford&#39;s EV sales increased 12% in the first half of the year, but executives say the growth rate would have been higher if the two plants building the Mach-E and F-150 Lightning weren&#39;t temporarily shut down for expansions.</p><p> <em>—Will Feuer contributed to this article</em> .</p><p> Write to Nora Eckert at <a href="mailto:nora.eckert@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">nora.eckert@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 17 Jul 2023 21:02:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/ford-cuts-price-of-ev-f-150-lightning-truck-by-up-to-17-2cc21c6a</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/ford-cuts-price-of-ev-f-150-lightning-truck-by-up-to-17-2cc21c6a<author><![CDATA[Nora Eckert]]></author><category> wsjcorp</category><category> Motor Vehicles</category><category> Passenger Cars</category><category> Alternative Fuel Vehicles</category><category> Automotive</category><category>容量/设施</category><category>Prices</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>市场/营销</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Ford Motor</category><category> F</category><category> Tesla</category><category> TSLA</category><category>福特</category><category>Jim Farley</category><category>容量</category><category>设施</category><category>prices</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>市场</category><category>营销</category><category>motor vehicles</category><category> passenger cars</category><category> alternative fuel vehicles</category><category> automotive</category></item></channel></rss>